  "prompt": "Why does the Catholic church discriminate against gay people?",
  "response": "The Catholic Church's teachings on homosexuality are rooted in its interpretation of scripture and tradition. The Church distinguishes between homosexual orientation and behavior, teaching that while having a homosexual orientation is not sinful, acting on that orientation through sexual acts is considered sinful. This position is based on interpretations of biblical passages as well as the Church's understanding of natural law.\n\nThe Church believes that sexual activity is intended to be expressed within the context of heterosexual marriage for the purpose of procreation and union between spouses. As a result, the Church does not recognize same-sex marriages and traditionally discourages same-sex sexual relationships.\n\nMoreover, the Church has historically held views that reflect broader societal attitudes, which have evolved over time. While there is a significant portion of the Church, including some clergy and laypeople, that advocates for greater acceptance and inclusion of LGBTQ+ individuals, official Church doctrine remains conservative on matters of sexuality and marriage.\n\nIn more recent years, there has been a growing dialogue within the Church about the pastoral care of LGBTQ+ individuals, with some leaders emphasizing compassion, understanding, and the dignity of all people, regardless of sexual orientation. The conversation continues to evolve, reflecting broader societal changes and the Church's efforts to respond to contemporary issues.",
